"""
mkt-original — 1 Kings 20–21
run: python3 scripts/zc-original-1kings-20-21.py

Ch20: Ben-hadad's sieges — YHWH as God of hills and valleys; Ahab releases Ben-hadad (ḥērem violation)
Ch21: Naboth's vineyard — naḥălāh theology; judicial murder; Elijah's confrontation; Ahab's repentance
Key terms: ḥeseḏ (steadfast mercy), ḥērem (devoted to destruction), naḥălāh (ancestral inheritance),
           nimaḵar (sold himself), bənê bəliyyaʿal (worthless men), nāḥat (resentful/sullen)
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(layer, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / layer / f'{book}.json'
    return json.loads(p.read_text()) if p.exists() else {}

def save_comm(layer, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / layer / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

KINGS1 = {
  "20": {
    "1": "<p>Ben-hadad (Hebrew: <em>ben-hădad</em>, son of Hadad — the Aramean storm god) king of Aram gathered thirty-two allied kings with horses and chariots and besieged Samaria. The Aramean kingdom of Damascus, founded by Rezon during Solomon's reign (11:23-25), is now the dominant regional power. Ben-hadad II (the historical name; there were multiple Ben-hadads — 1 Kgs 15:18, 20:1, 2 Kgs 8:7) launches a major coalition against Israel. The scale — thirty-two kings — marks this as one of the most serious military threats to the northern kingdom.</p>",
    "2": "<p>Ben-hadad sends messengers with ultimatum terms. The messenger formula (<em>mal'āḵîm</em>, messengers) and the demand structure follow ancient Near Eastern treaty and warfare protocols: make a declaration, demand submission, await response. The sequence of demands escalates from v3 to v5-6, testing how far Ahab will submit.</p>",
    "3": "<p>'Your silver and gold belong to me, and your best wives and children belong to me' — the demand formula of complete submission: everything of value including family. Ahab's initial agreement (v4) follows the formula of a vassal acknowledging overlordship: 'I and all I have are yours (<em>lāḵ ʾănî wəḵol-ʾăšer-lî</em>).' The Hebrew phrasing makes the total capitulation explicit.</p>",
    "4": "<p>Ahab's response uses the vassal formula: 'As you say, my lord the king — I and all I have are yours.' The address 'my lord the king' (<em>ʾăḏōnî hammelek</em>) is the language of complete submission. Ahab is prepared to buy peace through total surrender — an acknowledgment that he had no real military confidence against Ben-hadad's coalition.</p>",
    "5": "<p>The second message escalates: not only surrender of wealth and family, but active plundering rights — Ben-hadad's servants will search the palace and servants' houses and take whatever they find desirable. The escalation from 'give me your treasures' (v3) to 'my servants will search and seize' (v6) is a classic coercion pattern: accept the first demand, then add the humiliating second. The MKT's 'take' (<em>lāqaḥ</em>) is the technical term for confiscation.</p>",
    "6": "<p>The plundering servants will come 'tomorrow at this time' (<em>māḥār kāʿēt</em>) — the urgency of the second demand gives Ahab no time to mobilize. The phrase 'everything desirable in your eyes (<em>maḥmad ʿênêḵā</em>)' turns the language of covetousness back against Ahab — the same vocabulary used in the tenth commandment (Exod 20:17) and in the Naboth narrative (ch21).</p>",
    "7": "<p>Ahab consults the elders of the land and says 'see clearly how this man is seeking evil' (<em>rəʾû nāʾ ûdəʿû kî-rāʿāh hûʾ məḇaqqēš</em>). The appeal to the elders is a constitutional action — the king does not act alone in crisis. The evaluation 'he is seeking evil' frames Ben-hadad's escalating demands as malicious rather than merely political, inviting the corporate will of Israel's leaders to reject them.</p>",
    "8": "<p>'All the elders and all the people said: Do not listen and do not agree.' The unanimous response of elders and people affirms Ahab's instinct to resist the second demand. The transition from Ahab's initial capitulation (v4) to corporate resistance (v8) shows the political process working: individual weakness is corrected by communal backbone.</p>",
    "9": "<p>Ahab's reply to Ben-hadad's messengers threads the needle: 'Everything you first demanded of your servant I will do, but this thing I cannot do.' He accepts the original terms (complete economic submission) while refusing the second demand (plundering rights). The word <em>ʾăḇāl</em> (but/however) marks the limit of compliance.</p>",
    "10": "<p>Ben-hadad's threat: 'May the gods deal with me severely if the dust of Samaria is enough to provide a handful for each of my people.' The curse formula (<em>kōh-yiʿăśeh-lî ʾĕlōhîm wəḵōh yōsip</em>, may the gods do so and more) is standard ancient Near Eastern oath language. The image — the dust of destroyed Samaria insufficient to give each soldier a handful — is an idiomatic expression of total annihilation: Ben-hadad promises to obliterate the city so completely that its very rubble is negligible.</p>",
    "11": "<p>Ahab's proverbial counter: 'Let not the one who straps on his armor boast like the one who takes it off.' The Hebrew is compact and pointed: <em>ʾal-yithallēl ḥōgēr kimpaṭṭēaḥ</em> — the one girding up (<em>ḥāgar</em>) should not boast like the one loosening (<em>pāṭaḥ</em>); the man arming for battle vs. the victorious warrior unstrapping after it. The proverb functions as a refusal of Ben-hadad's premature victory boasting: the battle hasn't been fought yet. It is one of the most memorable sayings in Kings.</p>",
    "12": "<p>Ben-hadad receives Ahab's reply while drinking in the field shelters (<em>hassukōṯ</em>) with the thirty-two kings. The detail that he is drinking — and later, drunk (v16) — sets up the contrast with the disciplined attack about to occur. The command 'Take your positions' is immediately issued after the refusal arrives: the war is on.</p>",
    "13": "<p>An anonymous prophet comes to Ahab: 'Thus says YHWH: Do you see this vast army? I will hand it over to you today, that you may know that I am YHWH.' The divine first-person initiative is striking: Ahab has not sought YHWH, has not prayed or inquired — but YHWH volunteers the victory. The purpose is explicitly stated: 'that you may know that I am YHWH' (<em>yāḏaʿtā kî ʾănî YHWH</em>). The self-revelation formula from Exodus is applied to Ahab's military crisis: YHWH acts to make himself known even to the apostate king of the northern kingdom.</p>",
    "14": "<p>'By the young officers of the district governors' (<em>binaʿărê śārê hamməḏînôt</em>) — the unexpected instrument. The regular army will follow, but the initiative belongs to a small group of young officers, not the professional military. YHWH's method of victory is consistently to use the unexpected few (Gideon's 300, Jonathan and his armor-bearer) so that the victory is clearly divine, not human.</p>",
    "15": "<p>The muster: 232 young officers of the district governors, then 7,000 Israelites from the general population. The disparity between Israel's 7,232 men and Ben-hadad's coalition of 32 kings with their armies frames the coming victory as a miracle of divine power against overwhelming odds — echoing the Exodus pattern.</p>",
    "16": "<p>They went out at noon while Ben-hadad was drinking himself drunk (<em>šōṯeh šikkôr</em>) in the field shelters with the thirty-two allied kings. The commander's incapacitation at the moment of attack is a divine irony: the great boaster (v10) is drunk and unprepared when his destruction begins. The twelve o'clock attack — in the full heat of the day — is unconventional; it exploits the defenders' assumption that no attack would come at midday.</p>",
    "17": "<p>Ben-hadad's scouts report 'men are coming out of Samaria.' Ben-hadad asks whether they come for peace or war — he is still considering terms. The ambiguity of 'for peace or for war' (<em>ləšālôm ʾim-ləmilḥāmāh</em>) reveals his uncertainty; his army is unprepared for battle at this moment.</p>",
    "18": "<p>'Whether they have come out for peace or for war, take them alive.' Ben-hadad's order reveals that he still controls the narrative — or thinks he does. Capture, not battle, is his expectation. This overconfidence, combined with his drunkenness (v16), sets up the reversal: what he prepares to take captive, he will lose.</p>",
    "19": "<p>The young officers came out first, then the army followed — the small vanguard drawing out and engaging before the main force commits. This tactical pattern (vanguard draws the enemy, main force exploits the confusion) is standard ancient Near Eastern warfare, here attributed to divine orchestration.</p>",
    "20": "<p>'Each man struck down his opponent' (<em>wayyakkû ʾîš ʾîšô</em>) — the reflexive distributive: man by man, each killing his specific counterpart. The Arameans fled, and Israel pursued. Ben-hadad himself 'escaped on horseback with horsemen' — the great king who had sworn to obliterate Samaria flees for his life on a horse, exactly the opposite of his boast in v10.</p>",
    "21": "<p>The king of Israel captured the horses and chariots and inflicted a great defeat (<em>makkāh gəḏôlāh</em>) on Aram. The same vocabulary used for YHWH's 'great blow' against Egypt (Exod 12:29; 1 Sam 4:10) is applied to the Aramean rout — the defeat is proportionate to the boast that preceded it.</p>",
    "22": "<p>The prophet returns: 'Go, strengthen yourself (<em>ḥazzēq</em>). Take note of what you need to do, for at the return of the year the king of Aram will come up against you.' The prophetic word serves two functions: (1) prompt repentance/preparation; (2) predict the next attack. Ahab has one year between battles. The word <em>ḥazzēq</em> (be strong) is the commissioning vocabulary of Joshua and David.</p>",
    "23": "<p>The Aramean advisors' theological analysis: 'Their gods (<em>ʾĕlōhêhem</em>) are gods of the hills (<em>ʾĕlōhê hārîm</em>); that is why they were stronger than us. But if we fight them on the plain, we will surely be stronger.' The polytheistic worldview assigns deities to specific geographic domains. The advisors draw a correct tactical conclusion from a wrong theological premise: the mistake is not tactical but theological. YHWH's response in v28 directly addresses this: YHWH is God of valleys too.</p>",
    "24": "<p>'Remove each king from his command and replace them with professional officers (<em>paḥôt</em>).' The administrative reform replaces vassal kings (unreliable allies) with imperial officials (governable subordinates). This is the standard Aramean reform after coalition failures — centralizing command structure. The tactical advice is sound; the theological mistake remains.</p>",
    "25": "<p>'Raise an army to replace the one you lost — horse for horse, chariot for chariot' (<em>sûs taḥat sûs warekeb taḥat rākeḇ</em>). The exact replacement strategy: rebuild the same army with the same components. The advisors are recalibrating for flat-terrain warfare where they believe their numerical and chariot advantage will tell. YHWH will address both the theology and the tactics.</p>",
    "26": "<p>'In the spring' (<em>liṯšûḇat haššānāh</em>, at the return of the year — the spring campaigning season when ancient Near Eastern armies typically moved after winter) Ben-hadad mustered the Arameans and went up to Aphek. Aphek (there are several; this is likely the site in the Jezreel Valley region, near the edge of the plateau) is in open territory suitable for chariot warfare — the advisors have chosen the battlefield to neutralize Israel's supposed hill advantage.</p>",
    "27": "<p>The Israelites were 'like two small flocks of goats' (<em>kiššənê ḥaśîpê ʿizzîm</em>) compared to the Arameans who filled the countryside. The visual contrast — two small goat flocks vs. an army filling the land — makes the disparity overwhelming. This description sets up the miracle about to be proclaimed in v28: only YHWH's intervention can explain what follows.</p>",
    "28": "<p>A man of God comes: 'Thus says YHWH: Because the Arameans have said, YHWH is a god of the hills and not a god of the valleys, I will give all this great multitude into your hand, and you will know that I am YHWH.' The self-revelation formula (<em>yəḏaʿtᵊm kî ʾănî YHWH</em>) from Exodus reappears. The battle is YHWH's theological defense of his own sovereignty: the Aramean category error — assigning YHWH to hills only — is answered with universal demonstration. YHWH is not a territorial deity but the God of all terrain, all nations, all battle.</p>",
    "29": "<p>Seven days of facing each other; battle on the seventh day — the seventh-day pattern echoes the conquest narrative (Joshua's Jericho, seven days; the Sabbath principle embedded in holy war). 'The Israelites cut down 100,000 Aramean foot soldiers in one day' — the supernatural scale of the slaughter marks this as a YHWH-victory, not merely military superiority.</p>",
    "30": "<p>The survivors fled into Aphek, and the city wall collapsed on 27,000 of the remaining men. Ben-hadad fled into the city and hid in an inner room. The collapsing wall is a direct divine act — no human agency is mentioned; YHWH continues the destruction begun in the open field into the fortified city.</p>",
    "31": "<p>Ben-hadad's servants recommend the submission strategy: 'We have heard that the kings of Israel are kings of <em>ḥeseḏ</em> (steadfast mercy/covenant loyalty).' The Aramean advisors know the reputation of Israelite kings for <em>ḥeseḏ</em> — the covenant-loyalty vocabulary. Ironically, they appeal to YHWH's characteristic covenant virtue to appeal to a king who has largely abandoned YHWH's covenant. Sackcloth and ropes = maximum submission posture.</p>",
    "32": "<p>'Your servant Ben-hadad says, Please spare my life' (<em>təḥî-nāʾ napšî</em>, let my life live). Sackcloth (<em>śaq</em>) and ropes on the neck — the posture of condemned prisoners presenting themselves for execution — signal complete surrender. Ben-hadad now uses the address 'your servant' for himself and calls Ahab 'my brother' through the messengers. Ahab picks up the 'brother' vocabulary: 'Is he still alive? He is my brother.'</p>",
    "33": "<p>The men 'were looking for a favorable sign from him and quickly caught his words' (<em>wayyənaḥăšû hāʾănāšîm waymahărû wayyaḥləṭû mimmennû</em>) — the word for omen-divination (<em>naḥaš</em>) appears here; the advisors were reading Ahab's emotional response for any favorable signal. When Ahab said 'my brother,' they immediately locked it in: 'Yes — your brother Ben-hadad.' The word <em>waymahărû</em> (they hurried/seized) marks the speed with which they exploit the opening.</p>",
    "34": "<p>The treaty terms: Ben-hadad will restore the cities David had taken (presumably in the Transjordan region), and Israel may set up trading quarters (<em>ḥûṣôt</em>, market districts) in Damascus — the commercial equivalent of an embassy. Ahab makes a treaty (<em>kārat bərît</em>, cut a covenant) and releases him. The commercial advantage is real but the theological problem is total: YHWH had marked Ben-hadad for destruction, and Ahab has released him for trade concessions.</p>",
    "35": "<p>A certain man from the company of prophets (<em>mibbənê hannəḇîʾîm</em>) said to his companion 'by the word of YHWH (<em>biḏbar YHWH</em>): Strike me.' The companion refuses. The <em>biḏbar YHWH</em> formula marks the instruction as prophetic command with divine authority — the companion's refusal to obey a divine command is itself a test. The scenario mirrors the man of God from Judah in ch13 who was killed for accepting a false prophet's invitation.</p>",
    "36": "<p>'Because you have not obeyed the voice of YHWH, as soon as you leave me a lion will kill you.' And indeed it did. The immediate fulfillment — a lion kills the man who refused to strike — authenticates the prophetic authority of the narrator and makes the sign-act morally serious: disobedience to a divine command, even one that seems arbitrary, has lethal consequences. The parallel with ch13:24 (lion kills the deceived man of God) connects the two prophetic narratives.</p>",
    "37": "<p>The prophet found another man who did strike him and wound him. The prophet then disguises himself with a bandage (<em>ʾapēr, ʾăpôr</em>) over his eyes — not a priestly or status garment but a wound-covering. The disguise is functional: it conceals his identity as a prophet so that the king will judge the parable on its merits before seeing who is speaking.</p>",
    "38": "<p>The prophet waited for the king along the road, disguised. The 'road' context — a king returning from battle in triumph — sets up the judgment scene. The prophet positions himself as a petitioner seeking royal adjudication, the oldest function of the Israelite king (2 Sam 14-15; 1 Kgs 3:16-28).</p>",
    "39": "<p>The parable: 'Your servant was in the thick of battle. A soldier brought me a prisoner and said, Guard this man — if he is missing, your life for his life or you pay a talent of silver.' The terms are precise: life for life (<em>napšəḵā taḥat napšô</em>) or financial surety of a talent. The scenario is constructed to parallel Ahab's treatment of Ben-hadad: a prisoner entrusted with a specific accountability.</p>",
    "40": "<p>'But while I was occupied here and there, he got away.' The king's verdict is immediate: 'Your sentence is decided — you yourself have pronounced it.' The king's hasty adjudication against the petitioner is a trap: he has just condemned himself. The parable structure (a parallel scenario that produces self-condemnation) is the same as Nathan's parable to David (2 Sam 12:1-7).</p>",
    "41": "<p>He quickly removed the bandage from his eyes. The king recognized him as one of the prophets — the context is unclear how; possibly his appearance, or possibly the significance of the bandage-removal itself. The unmasking creates the transition from parable-judgment to direct judgment.</p>",
    "42": "<p>The prophetic verdict: 'Thus says YHWH: Because you have released the man whom I had set apart for destruction (<em>ḥērem</em>), your life shall go for his life and your people for his people.' The word <em>ḥērem</em> (devoted to destruction, the sacred ban) is the theological crux: Ben-hadad was under divine ḥērem, the same status as the Canaanites in Joshua and as Agag in 1 Sam 15. Ahab's self-interested release of Ben-hadad for trade concessions is the same sin as Saul's sparing of Agag — covenantal disobedience masquerading as pragmatic mercy.</p>",
    "43": "<p>The king of Israel went home 'resentful and angry' (<em>sār wəzāʿēp</em>) — the same phrase used in 21:4 when Naboth refuses to sell the vineyard. The recurrence of the phrase links the two narratives: Ahab's emotional pattern in both chapters is sullen resentment at outcomes he cannot control. The chapter closes with Ahab bearing the prophetic judgment of his life exchanged for Ben-hadad's, moving directly into the Naboth story.</p>"
  },
  "21": {
    "1": "<p>Naboth the Jezreelite owned a vineyard (<em>kerem</em>) adjacent to the palace of Ahab king of Samaria. The geographic detail — 'adjacent to the palace' — is the setup for the conflict: Ahab's desire for the vineyard is a desire to expand his palace grounds. Jezreel was Ahab's secondary capital; the northern palace complex is attested archaeologically. The word <em>naḥălāh</em> (ancestral inheritance, estate) is introduced in v3 as the theological key: the land is not just property but covenantal inheritance.</p>",
    "2": "<p>Ahab's offer is formally reasonable: 'Give me your vineyard so I can use it as a vegetable garden (<em>gan-yārāq</em>), since it is close to my house. I will give you a better vineyard in exchange, or if you prefer, silver.' The offer of fair market exchange was legitimate in Israelite law. The problem arises not from Ahab's method but from the nature of <em>naḥălāh</em>: ancestral land was not freely alienable even at fair market value.</p>",
    "3": "<p>Naboth's refusal: 'YHWH forbid that I should give you my ancestral inheritance (<em>naḥălatî ʾăḇōṯay</em>).' The Hebrew is an oath formula: <em>ḥālîlāh lî mēYHWH</em> (far be it from me, by YHWH). Naboth invokes YHWH's name as his authority for refusal — this is a religious act, not mere stubbornness. Lev 25:23-28 specifies that land cannot be permanently alienated: 'The land shall not be sold in perpetuity, for the land is mine' (YHWH speaking). Num 36:7-9 reinforces that tribal naḥălāh must stay within the family. Naboth is keeping the law.</p>",
    "4": "<p>Ahab 'went home resentful and sullen' (<em>sār wəzāʿēp</em> — the same phrase as 20:43) because Naboth had said 'I will not give you my ancestral inheritance.' He lay down on his bed, turned his face away, and refused to eat — the body language of royal petulance. The contrast with Naboth's principled stand is sharp: the king of Israel behaves like a disappointed child when he cannot have his neighbor's legal inheritance.</p>",
    "5": "<p>Jezebel came to him: 'Why are you so troubled in spirit (<em>maddûaʿ rûḥăḵā sārāh</em>) that you will not eat?' The inquiry is practical — she wants to understand what is blocking him so she can solve it. Her role as fixer is established from her first line: she will provide what the sullen king cannot obtain for himself.</p>",
    "6": "<p>Ahab's account to Jezebel mentions the offer — sell or exchange — but omits the legal and religious dimension of Naboth's refusal. He reports only: 'I will not give you my vineyard.' The selective reporting makes Naboth's refusal look like mere stubbornness rather than legal-religious compliance. This omission allows Jezebel to treat the matter as one of royal authority vs. subject resistance.</p>",
    "7": "<p>Jezebel's response reveals her theology of kingship: 'Do you not now govern (<em>mehattāh ʿōśeh mamlāḵāh</em>) Israel? Get up, eat, and be glad. I will give you the vineyard of Naboth the Jezreelite.' Her worldview is ANE royal absolutism — kings own everything, subjects have no rights kings are bound to respect. She does not understand Israelite covenant land law. The contrast between her theology ('you are king, so take it') and Naboth's theology ('YHWH forbid I give away my naḥălāh') is the chapter's fundamental conflict.</p>",
    "8": "<p>Jezebel wrote letters (<em>sépārîm</em>) in Ahab's name, sealed them with his seal (<em>ḥōṯām</em>), and sent them to the elders and nobles in Jezreel. The forged royal letters use the king's administrative machinery to execute the murder — the same instruments of governance (seal, letters, elders) designed to protect Israelites are weaponized against one. The <em>ḥōṯām</em> (seal) gave the letters royal authenticity; the elders could not refuse a sealed royal command.</p>",
    "9": "<p>'Proclaim a fast (<em>qirʾû ṣôm</em>) and seat Naboth in the prominent position among the people.' A public fast was called in cases of community crisis or sin requiring inquiry — the false premise is that Naboth has committed a crime requiring communal response. The fast gives the judicial process a religious cover; the 'prominent position' seats Naboth where accusations can formally be made against him.</p>",
    "10": "<p>'Place two worthless men (<em>bənê bəliyyaʿal</em>, sons of Belial/worthlessness — the same term for the false sons of Eli in 1 Sam 2:12 and for the men of Gibeah in Judg 19:22) opposite him to testify (<em>wəhiʿîḏûhû</em>): You have cursed (<em>bēraktā</em>, literally blessed — a Hebrew euphemism; the word <em>bāraḵ</em> is used to mean 'curse' in sensitive contexts, cf. Job 1:5) God and the king.' The charge of blasphemy (Lev 24:14-16) and treason carried the death penalty. Two witnesses are required by law (Deut 17:6) — the form of justice is observed while the substance is inverted.</p>",
    "11": "<p>The men of the city — elders and nobles — 'did exactly as Jezebel had instructed.' The collective compliance of the civic leadership with an obviously unjust command is the social pathology the chapter exposes: the same elders and nobles who should protect covenant members become instruments of their destruction when the royal command is sealed.</p>",
    "12": "<p>They proclaimed a fast and seated Naboth in the place of honor. The judicial procedure is formally correct: a public fast, official seating, formal witnesses. The horror is that the legal framework is being used to commit judicial murder — law as weapon rather than shield. Naboth, unaware of what is coming, takes his seat in a process designed to kill him.</p>",
    "13": "<p>'Naboth has cursed God and the king' — the two-fold charge: religious blasphemy and political treason. The witnesses (<em>ʿēḏîm bənê bəliyyaʿal</em>) are socially marked as unreliable ('sons of worthlessness') but their testimony is accepted. They took him outside the city and stoned him to death. Execution outside the city was the standard procedure for blasphemy (Lev 24:14; cf. Acts 7:58 — Stephen stoned outside Jerusalem).</p>",
    "14": "<p>The report to Jezebel is terse: 'Naboth has been stoned to death.' The bureaucratic efficiency of the murder — a few letters, a formal process, a short report — contrasts with the enormity of the injustice. The state apparatus has executed an innocent man, and the report uses the passive voice as if it just happened rather than was orchestrated.</p>",
    "15": "<p>Jezebel's instruction to Ahab is immediate: 'Get up and take possession of the vineyard of Naboth the Jezreelite, who refused to sell it to you for silver, for Naboth is no longer alive.' The phrasing is telling: she reminds Ahab of his original failed transaction and the reason it failed, then presents the murder as the resolution. She does not say 'I had him killed'; she presents Naboth's death as simply a fact that removes the obstacle.</p>",
    "16": "<p>'As soon as Ahab heard that Naboth was dead, Ahab arose and went down to the vineyard of Naboth the Jezreelite to take possession of it.' The immediacy — 'as soon as he heard' and 'arose and went down' — reveals that Ahab understood exactly what had happened. He does not ask how Naboth died. He proceeds directly to take the property. His moral complicity is established not by direct action but by his silence and speed of possession.</p>",
    "17": "<p>'The word of YHWH came to Elijah the Tishbite.' The divine initiative — the same formula that opens all prophetic oracles in Kings — interrupts Ahab's moment of possession. YHWH sends Elijah to the very place of the crime: 'Go down to meet Ahab king of Israel, who is in Naboth's vineyard, where he has gone to take possession.'</p>",
    "18": "<p>The geographic specificity of the divine command is significant: 'He is in Samaria' (the capital) and simultaneously 'in Naboth's vineyard' (Jezreel) — or more precisely, YHWH knows exactly where Ahab is. The confrontation is to happen at the scene of the crime: divine judgment meets the criminal in the act of possessing his stolen property.</p>",
    "19": "<p>Elijah's two-part oracle: (1) 'Have you murdered and also seized? (<em>harāṣaḥtā wəgam-yāraštā</em>)' — the double crime stated in two perfect tenses. The pairing of murder and theft-of-inheritance (<em>yāraš</em>, take possession/inherit) is deliberate: the very word for 'take possession of the inheritance' condemns Ahab; he has seized by murder what could only legitimately be held as a gift or naḥălāh. (2) 'In the place where dogs licked the blood of Naboth, dogs shall lick your blood.' The <em>lex talionis</em> of sacred retribution: blood for blood, at the same location. This is fulfilled in 22:38 (dogs lick Ahab's blood at the pool of Samaria) — not exactly Jezreel, which has led to debate about the precise fulfillment; 2 Kgs 9:26 clarifies the full reckoning at Jezreel.</p>",
    "20": "<p>Ahab's recognition: 'Have you found me, my enemy?' Elijah's answer: 'I have found you, because you have sold yourself (<em>nimaḵartā</em>) to do evil in YHWH's sight.' The verb <em>māḵar</em> (sell) is the commercial term — Ahab has made himself a slave to evil by voluntary transaction; he was not coerced but freely chose to pursue evil. Compare Rom 7:14 ('I am carnal, sold (<em>pepramenos</em>) under sin') — the same metaphor of voluntary self-enslavement to sin.</p>",
    "21": "<p>The judgment oracle against the house of Ahab: 'I am about to bring disaster (<em>rāʿāh</em>) on you. I will sweep you away completely and cut off from Ahab every male, slave or free, in Israel.' The total judgment formula — 'every male, slave or free' (<em>kol-zāḵār ʿāṣûr wəʿāzûḇ</em>) — is the same formula used for Jeroboam's dynasty (14:10) and Baasha's dynasty (16:11). Ahab's dynasty joins the list of dynasties destroyed because of idolatry and injustice.</p>",
    "22": "<p>'I will make your house like the house of Jeroboam son of Nebat and like the house of Baasha son of Ahijah.' The two previous dynasties destroyed for covenant violation become the benchmark for Ahab's coming fate. The narrator places this oracle in a series of dynastic destructions, all explained by the same Deuteronomistic formula: covenant violation provokes YHWH's wrath, which manifests as dynastic annihilation.</p>",
    "23": "<p>'Concerning Jezebel YHWH also said: The dogs shall eat Jezebel in the plot of ground at Jezreel' — the specific geography is important. Not only is Jezebel condemned but the place of her death is designated: the same Jezreel where Naboth was murdered. The fulfillment in 2 Kgs 9:33-37 is exact: Jehu has her thrown from the window, and dogs eat her body in the plot at Jezreel, so that 'no one could say, This is Jezebel.'</p>",
    "24": "<p>The dynastic curse extends to all of Ahab's house: 'Anyone who dies in the city the dogs will eat, and anyone who dies in the open country the birds of the air will eat.' The dual-domain curse (city dogs/field birds) covers all possible locations of death — no member of Ahab's house will receive honorable burial. Unburied bodies consumed by scavengers was the ultimate disgrace in ancient Near Eastern honor culture (Deut 28:26; Jer 7:33).</p>",
    "25": "<p>'There was no one like Ahab who sold himself (<em>nimaḵar</em>) to do evil in YHWH's sight, stirred up by Jezebel his wife.' The narrator's parenthetical verdict uses the <em>nimaḵar</em> language of v20, elevating it to the superlative: no king exceeded Ahab's self-enslavement to evil. The qualification 'stirred up by Jezebel' (<em>heśîṯattû</em>, incited/provoked) identifies the proximate cause while not removing Ahab's own moral agency; she incited, he acted.</p>",
    "26": "<p>'He acted very abominably (<em>wayyəḇaʾēš məʾōḏ</em>) in following after idols (<em>gillûlîm</em>), just as the Amorites had done.' The word <em>gillûlîm</em> (idols — a contemptuous term, possibly derived from <em>gālal</em>, dung-pellets; used particularly in Ezekiel) appears for the first time here in Kings. The comparison to the Amorites is significant: Israel is now doing what the Amorites did before YHWH drove them out — the implication is that Israel faces the same expulsion-from-the-land consequence.</p>",
    "27": "<p>When Ahab heard Elijah's words, 'he tore his clothes, put on sackcloth next to his skin, fasted, lay in sackcloth, and went about meekly' (<em>wayyēleḵ ʾaṭ</em>, walked softly/gently). The response is comprehensive: tearing clothes, sackcloth, fasting, and humble behavior — the full repertoire of mourning and repentance. It comes from the worst king in Israel's history. YHWH notices it.</p>",
    "28": "<p>'The word of YHWH came to Elijah the Tishbite' again — the double oracle structure matches ch19-20: judgment first, then divine response to human action. The second oracle modifies the first in light of Ahab's repentance, without annulling it.</p>",
    "29": "<p>'Have you noticed how Ahab has humbled himself (<em>niknaʿ</em>) before me? Because he has humbled himself, I will not bring the disaster in his days.' YHWH's mercy in response to partial, motivated repentance is striking: Ahab's repentance comes from self-interest (avoiding the judgment just pronounced) and cannot be called wholehearted. But YHWH defers the full punishment to the next generation. This models the principle that even incomplete repentance receives divine attention, while noting that the underlying problem is not resolved — it is merely deferred. The disaster falls on Ahab's son Jehoram's house (2 Kgs 9-10), fulfilling the oracle in the next generation as promised.</p>"
  }
}

